affectation. This disturbing conflation of two opposing conditions encapsulates Hamlet’s much-discussed problem: he cannot tell the difference between genuine affection and deceptive affectation. Drawing on a growing field of scholarship engaged in the study of rhetoric in early modern English texts, Indict the Author of Affection explores how Shakespeare’s extensive and self-conscious use of catachresis involves not only far-fetched metaphors but subversive new meanings that can infect familiar words, dramatizing his characters’ psychological conflicts and producing a rich but treacherous instability in language itself.Indict the Author of Affection brings to Hamlet a groundbreaking analysis engaged with the complex, wide-ranging, and contentious discourse concerning affectation as a rhetorical, moral, and aesthetic issue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAffect (Psychology) in literature. 0aFigures of speech in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aAristotle.  aBaldassare Castiglione.  aBen Jonson.  aCicero.  aEliot.  aJacques Derrida.  aJacques Lacan.  aJames Joyce.  aJean-Paul Sartre.  aJohn Lyly.  aMichel Foucault.  aMichel de Montaigne.  aOscar Wilde.  aQuintilian.  aRene Girard.  aRichard Lanham.  aSigmund Freud.  aSir Philip Sidney.  aThomas Nashe.  aWilliam Shakespeare.  aYeats.  aaffect.  aaffected.  aaffetazione.  aantic.  aauthorship.  acacozelia.  acourtier.  acuriosity.  acurious.  adecorum.  adisgrace.  aeloquence.  aenargeia.  agrace.  aimpropriety.  aindecorum.  ainfection.  amala adfectatio.  amelancholy.  ametaphor.  amisogyny.  apassion.  aperformative.  apropriety.  arecklessness.  arhetoric.  aself-deception.  asprezzatura.  atheatricality.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/97802280